com.interpss.core.algo.path

Interface NetPathWalkAlgorithm<TBus extends Bus,TBranch extends Branch>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    com.hazelcast.nio.serialization.DataSerializable, org.eclipse.emf.ecore.EObject, INetBVisitor<TBus,TBranch>, NameTag, org.eclipse.emf.common.notify.Notifier
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    ActivePowerPathWalkAlgorithm, LossAllocationAlgorithm
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    DistPathLfAlgorithm, LossAllocationAlgorithmImpl, NetPathWalkAlgorithmImpl

    public interface NetPathWalkAlgorithm<TBus extends Bus,TBranch extends Branch>
extends NameTag, INetBVisitor<TBus,TBranch>
    A base for network flow path walk algorithm implementation. The walk could be along the flow path or opposite to the flow path. For example, one can walk through a network along/opposite to the active power flow path after load flow converged. The walk through algorithm is implemented in the visit method, which is a generic implementation of network path walk-through. - The walk could be along the network flow path direction (source -> sink) or in opposite direction (sink -> source) - For the source -> sink direction, the walk starts from buses with only out-direction branches and ends with buses with only into-direction branches. - bus object walking includes 1) if source -> sink direction and no into-direction branch, turn the bus.walkStatus = true and perform some action to the bus object 2) if source -> sink direction, turn all out-direction branches walkStatus = true, and perform some action to the branch object A generic algorithm to walk along/opposite path. The path direction itself is domain problem specific. For example, the walk could be along active power flow or current flow direction.

    The following features are supported:

    • Direction
    • Bus Walker
    • Branch Walker
    See Also:
    PathAlgorithmPackage.getNetPathWalkAlgorithm()
